#gal-3-15 {
 {
   TODO: <pre>http://www.ambassador4christ.net/RightDivideronYoutube/02/2014-06-29-Galatians3v15-21-Law_does_not_void_God%27s_promises.txt
Galatians 3:15-21  The law does not void God’s promises June 29, 2014
3:15  The man’s covenant in view is the one made with Abram in Genesis 15:5-17.
 In that covenant, Abram’s seed is to be as the stars in heaven (Genesis 15:5),
 not as the dust of the earth (Genesis 13:15-17).
 Both come together in Christ (Genesis 22:17).
 Thus, Abraham is the father of all believers (Romans 4:11-16).
3:16  Only by the Holy Spirit’s revelation through Paul do we know that the seed
 of Genesis 15:5 is Christ. Otherwise, we would assume the seed is Israel.
3:17  In Genesis 15:17, a smoking furnace and a burning lamp are part of the covenant.
 The smoking furnace is God (Exodus 19:18).
 The burning lamp is Christ (Psalm 119:105, John 1:1,9, Revelation 1:15, Psalm 12:6).
 The covenant was between Abram and Christ (the seed) with Christ doing all the work.
 The covenant was witnessed by God, who was the smoking furnace.
3:17  The law came 430 years later. It was a covenant between God and Israel (Exodus 19:5-9).
3:18  The law’s covenant is conditional upon Israel’s performance.
3:19  The law was added because of Israel’s transgressions in unbelief
 (Exodus 14:10-12; 15:23-24; 16:2-3; 17:1-3).
 Because the law’s covenant is between God and man, a mediator between God and Israel
 was required (Exodus 19:3,7; John 1:17).
3:20-21  Since Christ fulfilled the provisions of the covenant with Abram,
 God is free to bring about the promises of God.
 Since man failed in obeying the law, righteousness comes from God’s promises, not from the law.
   </pre>
 }
 {
  <i>Testament</i>: <a class='kom' href='#Imt-26-28'>Mt&nbsp;26,28</a>.
 }
#}
